    "thermo": { n: 'Chemical thermodynamics defines reaction spontaneity through Gibbs Free Energy. Negative ΔG means the reaction will proceed spontaneously.', q: 'Hess\'s Law states that the total enthalpy change of a reaction is:', o: ['Independent of the pathway taken', 'Dependent on the reaction pathway', 'Always zero', 'Always positive'], a: 'Independent of the pathway taken' },
    "electro": { n: 'Electrochemistry studies electron transfer in oxidation-reduction. Galvanic cells convert chemical energy to electrical energy via spontaneous redox.', q: 'In an electrochemical cell, oxidation always occurs at the:', o: ['Anode', 'Cathode', 'Salt Bridge', 'Electrolyte'], a: 'Anode' },
    "kinetics": { n: 'Chemical kinetics explores reaction rates. The Arrhenius equation links the rate constant inversely to the activation energy barrier.', q: 'A catalyst increases the reaction rate by:', o: ['Lowering the activation energy', 'Increasing the temperature', 'Increasing the reactant concentration', 'Raising the enthalpy'], a: 'Lowering the activation energy' },
    "quantum-chem": { n: 'Quantum chemistry models electrons as wavefunctions extending across the molecule, predicting molecular orbitals instead of discrete orbits.', q: 'The Born-Oppenheimer approximation assumes that because nuclei are much heavier than electrons, their motion can be treated as:', o: ['Stationary relative to electrons', 'Moving at light speed', 'Identical to electrons', 'Uncertain'], a: 'Stationary relative to electrons' },
    "spectroscopy": { n: 'Spectroscopy studies light-matter interaction. NMR spectroscopy utilizes magnetic alignment of nuclei to determine molecular structure.', q: 'Infrared (IR) spectroscopy primarily identifies organic compounds by detecting what property of molecules?', o: ['Bond Vibrations', 'Electron Excitation', 'Nuclear Spin', 'Mass'], a: 'Bond Vibrations' },
    "chromatography": { n: 'Chromatography sorts physical mixtures based on the varying affinities of components towards a stationary phase versus a mobile fluid phase.', q: 'In Gas Chromatography (GC), the mobile phase is typically:', o: ['An inert carrier gas (e.g., Helium)', 'A liquid solvent', 'A solid powder', 'A polymer gel'], a: 'An inert carrier gas (e.g., Helium)' },
    "lab": { n: 'Laboratory techniques demand precise measurement and handling. Titration quantifies the concentration of an unknown solution via a standard reagent.', q: 'When diluting concentrated acid, what is the proper safety procedure?', o: ['Always add acid to water', 'Always add water to acid', 'Mix rapidly with a metal spoon', 'Heat the mixture before adding'], a: 'Always add acid to water' },
    "safety": { n: 'Chemical safety strictly follows Material Safety Data Sheets (MSDS) detailing flammability, toxicity, and proper emergency neutralizations.', q: 'Which pictorial symbol universally indicates a substance is corrosive?', o: ['A liquid dripping onto a hand and metal, eroding them', 'A skull and crossbones', 'A flame', 'An exploding bomb'], a: 'A liquid dripping onto a hand and metal, eroding them' },
    "periodic": { n: 'The Periodic Table relies on periodic trends. Electronegativity increases up and to the right, dictating polar bonding behaviors.', q: 'Which group of elements possesses a completely filled valence shell, rendering them highly unreactive?', o: ['Noble Gases', 'Alkali Metals', 'Halogens', 'Transition Metals'], a: 'Noble Gases' },
    "bonding": { n: 'Chemical bonding relies on electron sharing or transfer. VSEPR theory uses electron pair repulsion to predict the exact 3D geometry of molecules.', q: 'According to VSEPR theory, a molecule with a central atom bonded to 4 atoms with 0 lone pairs has what geometry?', o: ['Tetrahedral', 'Trigonal Planar', 'Bent', 'Octahedral'], a: 'Tetrahedral' },
    "states": { n: 'States of matter dictate molecular clustering. A supercritical fluid forms above the critical point, possessing properties of both gases and liquids.', q: 'The process of a solid turning directly into a gas without passing through a liquid phase is called:', o: ['Sublimation', 'Deposition', 'Evaporation', 'Condensation'], a: 'Sublimation' },
    "stoicho": { n: 'Stoichiometry uses balanced chemical equations to calculate reactant and product masses based on mole ratios.', q: 'If 2 moles of H2 react with 1 mole of O2 to form water, what is the limiting reactant if you have 4 moles of H2 and 1 mole of O2?', o: ['O2', 'H2', 'Both are exact', 'Neither'], a: 'O2' },
    "acids": { n: 'Acids and bases dictate hydronium exchange. Brønsted-Lowry defines an acid as a proton (H+) donor and a base as a proton acceptor.', q: 'The pH scale is logarithmic. A solution with a pH of 3 is how many times more acidic than a solution with pH 5?', o: ['100 times', '20 times', '2 times', '10 times'], a: '100 times' },
    "bases": { n: 'Bases typically donate OH- ions or accept protons. Buffer solutions contain a weak acid and its conjugate base to resist pH changes.', q: 'Which compound is a classic example of a strong base?', o: ['Sodium Hydroxide (NaOH)', 'Ammonia (NH3)', 'Acetic Acid (CH3COOH)', 'Water (H2O)'], a: 'Sodium Hydroxide (NaOH)' },
    "redox": { n: 'Redox reactions involve the transfer of electrons. Oxidation involves the loss of electrons (OIL), while reduction is the gain of electrons (RIG).', q: 'In the reaction Zn + Cu²⁺ → Zn²⁺ + Cu, which species is being oxidized?', o: ['Zn', 'Cu²⁺', 'Zn²⁺', 'Cu'], a: 'Zn' },
    "equilibrium": { n: 'Chemical equilibrium occurs when the forward and reverse reaction rates are equal. Le Chatelier\'s principle predicts the shift when stress is applied.', q: 'If you add more of a reactant to a system at equilibrium, the system will shift:', o: ['To the right (favoring products)', 'To the left (favoring reactants)', 'It won\'t shift', 'Temperature will drop immediately'], a: 'To the right (favoring products)' },
